  "prompt": "What are the chemical properties of a candle?",
  "response": "Here are some key chemical properties of a candle:\n\n1. Composition\n- Typically made of paraffin wax (hydrocarbon compound)\n- Consists of carbon and hydrogen atoms\n\n2. Combustion Process\n- When lit, wax melts and is drawn up the wick via capillary action\n- Vaporizes and reacts with oxygen in the air\n- Undergoes chemical reaction: C(n)H(2n+2) + O2 \u2192 CO2 + H2O\n\n3. Chemical Reaction\n- Releases heat and light during burning\n- Produces carbon dioxide and water vapor\n- Exothermic reaction\n\n4. Physical State Changes\n- Solid wax at room temperature\n- Melts around 37-54\u00b0C\n- Vaporizes at higher temperatures\n\n5. Molecular Structure\n- Long hydrocarbon chains\n- Primarily saturated hydrocarbons\n- Low molecular weight\n\n6. Energy Properties\n- High energy content\n- Releases approximately 42 kJ/g when burned\n- Combustible material\n\n7. Reactivity\n- Reacts with oxygen during combustion\n- Flammable at high temperatures\n- Relatively stable at room temperature\n\nThese properties describe the fundamental chemical characteristics of a typical candle.",
